    "Hardisty, Johnson and Weber (id74) conducted a framing experiment among 889 Americans to assess how labelling charges for environmental costs as either an earmarked tax or an offset included as a surcharge for emitted carbon dioxide affects consumer choices.",
    "Their results indicate that cost framing changed preferences for both respondents self-identifying as Republicans and Independents.",
    "Democrats' preferences were not significantly affected by these frames.",
    "Conversely, the LASSOplus results did not confirm any significant main or heterogeneous treatment effects reported by the original study.",
    "The study by Bolson and Druckmann (id83) investigates the role of partisan group identity and the politicization of science in weakening the impact of a scientific-consensus-based message about human-induced climate change in the United States."
  ],
